Activity Name: CA: BFS-15-003: International Wheat Yield Partnership (Wheat Yield Network)
Disaggregate Name: Number of individuals participating in USG food security programs [IM-level]
Deviation Narrative: Deviation: Some seed shipments were consolidated (grouped under one collaborator name per institution) to reduce shipment costs. Therefore, fewer people are registered in the database than actual users. Similarly, male/female does not represent the final user distribution.
Collection Period Comments: Selected wheat lines and technologies were distributed to 113 collaborators from 54 different countries, including national wheat programs worldwide and institutions in the public, private, and academic sectors

Activity Name: Feed the Future Innovative Maize and Cowpea Technologies to Increase Food and Nutrition Security in Africa: pod borer resistant Bt cowpea sub-activity
Disaggregate Name: Number of individuals participating in USG food security programs [IM-level]
Deviation Narrative:
In Nigeria, the project trained the seed companies and their outgrowers, extension agents and framers on the good agronomic practices, use of irrigation facilities for dry season production, post harvest handling, stewardship requirements and use of digitatl tools like SAMAWATI App for monitoring, data collection and incident reporting. 

In Ghana, 100 farmers participated in establishment and management of the demo plots towards variety release. 
In Burkina Faso, 62 farmers were engaged for the National Performance Trials towards variety release.

Disaggregate Name: Number of individuals participating in USG food security programs [IM-level]
Deviation Narrative:
In Nigeria, the project trained the seed companies and their outgrowers, extension agents and framers on the good agronomic practices, use of irrigation facilities for dry season production, post harvest handling, stewardship requirements and use of digitatl tools like SAMAWATI App for monitoring, data collection and incident reporting. 

In Ghana, 100 farmers participated in establishment and management of the demo plots towards variety release. 
In Burkina Faso, 62 farmers were engaged for the National Performance Trials towards variety release.

Disaggregate Name: Number of individuals participating in USG food security programs [IM-level]
Deviation Narrative: We had targeted 12 community health promoters and 8 nutritionists from the county government for a 2-day long training on the nutrition-sensitive interventions and practices that can be applied to address the nutrition gaps in the county as part of the social behaviour change communication strategy/ intervention. However, as part of the co-creation process, the County government proposed inclusion of Health promotion officers who are critical in ensuring the right information is passed to the communities. This increased the number to 27 participants.

Operating Unit: Bureau for Resilience and Food Security (RFS)
Disaggregate Name: Number of individuals participating in USG food security programs [IM-level]
Collection Period Comments: ILCI engaged over 300 researchers from 13 countries (including Mexico and Ghana counted under the Global geography) to collaborate on applying improved tools, technologies, and methods to national breeding program priorities to develop improved varieties of sorghum, cowpea, pearl and finger millet, sweet potato, and common bean. Additionally, through their work identifying farmer and consumer preferences, ILCI's work reached more smallholder producers and members of the private sector and government agencies. This work included training cattle producers in Costa Rica on silage capacities to use sorghum as fodder, exchange workshops in Senegal exploring the potentials around essential oil production, inclusive stakeholder learning platforms to encourage Kenyan farmers to cook with finger millet, and training Malawian government extension agents and private sector actors on the village based agent and small pack approach to multiplying and distributing seeds.

Operating Unit: Bureau for Resilience and Food Security (RFS)
Disaggregate Name: Number of individuals participating in USG food security programs [IM-level]
Deviation Narrative: Multiregion/Global participants are researchers from Ghana and Mexico.

Disaggregate Name: Number of individuals participating in USG food security programs [IM-level]
Deviation Narrative:
For age disaggregation:
In Zambia S34D reached 2 youth out of target of 10 (20%) of ADA workers.
For farmers, the ADAs reached 48/500 (10% of target).

In Kenya standard seed activity, there were no youth (under 30) reached.
For the Stop Bad Seed in Tanzania activity, all participants were 30+.
in Zambia the activity was to promote access to locally grown legume seed through use of agricultural development agents. S34D reached 85.6% of farmers because the Agricultural Development Agents (who were seed growers) had limited capacity in producing seed.  During that year they produced seed that could only serve 675 farmers.    Seed is what most farmers are interested in and since a significant amount of the farmers could not access it due to limited supply, they were discouraged from participating in other project activities like field days and trainings.  

Limitation in the capacity of Zambian ADAs to produce seed largely attributed to lack of resources to buy Early Generation Seed (EGS)  due to the high cost, and the unlikelihood of repeat purchase by farmers post project, The CRS activity (non S34D) did not purchase EGS during that year as a measure of promoting sustainability of project activities beyond the life of the project. There was also a shift in farmer interest from pigeon pea towards soyabeans during this season because of high soyabean prices incurred in the previous season.  This also resulted in some farmers leaving the project in preference to other organizations (such as?) that were taking up large numbers of farmers (can this be estimated / quantified) willing to produce soyabeans

In Guatemala, the bean and potato training was a multi-day training (2.5 days) and it was difficult for many attendees to participate, due to the length of the training, long distance to the training site as well as due to needs taking care of their farms and fields. Due to prior training experience, ASOCUCH attempted to mitigate this issue by carrying out the 2.5 day training over a two week period (one day one week, and remaining 1.5 days the following week).   They have used this training experience as a lesson learned and may consider stretching out future trainings over a three week period (one day per week) in order to increase attendance. 

In Kenya through the standard seed activity, S34D reached 165% of target figures. This was due to their prior work carried out by Agri Experience in Kenya and their strong relationship with KEPHIS. 

In Tanzania, the Stop Bad Seed activity began mid year, after the workplan had been submitted and no targets were available; thus the activity used the actual numbers reached as targets.
Collection Period Comments:
Under this indicator, the project reached 3,351 individuals out of a target of 3,601 (93%).
For a breakdown, In Zambia the project reached 39/40 (98%) Agricultural Development Agents and these ADAs reached 1709 farmers trained from a target of 2000 (86%). 
In Guatemala, the project reached 68/85 farmers (75%). 
In Kenya the project reached 165/100 target (165%).
In Tanzania, the project reach 1,376 farmers (100%).   

Regarding gender: 
In Zambia S34D reached 24 males (78% of target) and 15 female ADA agents (188% of target).    For farmers in Zambia, the activity reached 1,051 males (75%) and 656 females (109%). 
In Guatemala, S34D reach 49 males (72% of target) and 15 females (88% of target). 
In Kenya S34D reach 101 males (135%) and 64 females (256% of target)
In Tanzania no gender disaggregates are available.
